<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>DCLG’s written submission on the inquiry into local government procurement</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Written submission from the Department of Communities and Local Government (LPG 63)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Summary</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Local government spends £58 billion</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> per year procuring goods and services. This note sets out how DCLG is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">incentivising</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> local government to open up its procurement practices, and become more efficient, transparent and accountable to local communities.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Significant changes have been made to central government procurement, examined recently by the Public Administration Select Committee in their report published on 16 July 2013</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. The principles behind those changes are the ones councils should be adopting, such as eliminating Pre Qualification Questionnaires for low value contracts as discussed on page 6. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">In July 2013</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">, t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">he Federation for Small Businesses </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">published research which found </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> councils are transforming their procurement process. Specifically they found that there has been a noticed increase in the number of local authorities who adopt different processes for below EU threshold tenders (85% from 74% in 2012)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">W</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">recognise</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> progress has been made</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">however </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">there are still too many councils using overly bureaucratic, disproportionate procurement processes, which unnecessarily discriminate against smaller businesses, and which are not transparent to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">heir local communities. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This has been highlighted by the Mystery Shopper Scheme, which is discussed on page 7. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">I</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">t is not for central government to dictate local procurement practices, strategies or structures, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">but </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">we</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> have an important role in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">incentivising</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> service transformation and encouraging</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">innovation t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">hrough a number of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">mechanisms:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt; text-decoration:underline">Rewarding success</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Through “50 Ways to Save – Examples of Sensible Savings in Local Government”</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">we provided examples </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">procurement savings in both big and small projects, by procuring better, tackling fraud, and collaborating</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">, as discussed in detail on pages 6 and 7</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">In January, with support from Lord Young, we started the ‘Best councils to do business with’ contest. The criteria assessed a council’s overall approach to opening up their procurement practices. 67 strong entries</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> were assessed </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">by a panel which included industry representation from the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Federation of Small Businesses</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">, Co</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">nfederation of British Industry</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> and British Chambers of Commerce. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">The winners were </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">announced on 15 May</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">at a reception at </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">10 Downing Street</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">and each showed </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">clear </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">evidence of best practice, valuing small businesses and putting them at the heart of service delivery. We will be working with these exemplar councils to showcase </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">their work. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We are also currently assessing bids for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">this</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> year</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s Transformation Challenge Award. £6.9m will be available to councils who wish to make savings by transforming and sharing their services with others. We expect to see the innovative use of procurement functions to feature strongly in those bids, which will enable us to reward success and promote exemplars</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> even further</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.     </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt; text-decoration:underline">Focused intervention </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Central government can act as a key facilitator in specific service areas where significant savings need to be made. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">o assist with</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> efficiency and transparency in fire procurement </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">the Department is currently undertaking a joint research project with the Chief Fire Officers Associat</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">ion to capture procurement data</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">. This is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> due to complete in late 2013. Furthermore, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Facing th</span><a name="_Hlt365380325"></a><a name="_Hlt365380326"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">e</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> Future</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> - t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">he independent review of efficiency and operations in fire and rescue authorities in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">England</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">includes </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">a section on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">fire procurement. The Government response to the Review will be published shortly. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Helvetica 45 Light'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Helvetica 45 Light'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">DCLG, BIS, the Cabinet Office and the Local Government Association have been working together to look at what more councils can do to get best value from their procurement of construction projects.  The government’s industrial strategy for construction was launched on 2nd July</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:'Helvetica 45 Light'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> and sets out how we can work with the construction industry to ensure the </span><span style="font-family:'Helvetica 45 Light'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:'Helvetica 45 Light'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> continues to thrive in the face of increasing global competition. The strategy includes a commitment for the Local Government Association to establish a construction procurement group and develop a construction procurement strategy for local government by Spring 2014</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Governing legislation and recommended practice </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Central government clearly has a role to play in ensuring legislation promotes the procurement principles we advocate, whilst allowing significant freedom and flexibility to allow local practices to be adapted to suit local markets and contracts.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">We will shortly be undertaking a significant consultation on procurement reforms across the whole public sector, which follow on from Lord Young’s report </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Growing Your </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Business</span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">. The consultation will focus on some key themes: </span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.37pt; padding-left:7.33pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Pre-Qualification;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> eliminating the use of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Pre Qualification Questionnaires</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> for low value contracts, mandating a core </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Pre Qualification Questionnaire</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> with standard questions for high value contracts, and allowing suppliers to provide </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Pre Qualification Questionnaire</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> data only once.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.37pt; padding-left:7.33pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Transparency</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">: ensuring all new contract opportunities and contract awards are advertised online and the public sector reports its performance on spend with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">small businesses </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">and centrally negotiated deals.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.37pt; padding-left:7.33pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Payment and finance</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">: ensuring contractors pay their suppliers on time; consideration of whether performance bonds can be an unnecessary barrier for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">small businesses</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">, and encouraging the use of e-invoicing in the public sector. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">These principles would simplify and standardise the bidding, payment and advertising of contracts, and would remove the complexity, cost and inconsistency when trying to sell to more than one local authority o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">r public sector body. This will</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> help </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">small businesses</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> access the £230 billion per year that is spent on goods and services across the whole public sector</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Furthermore the Department represented local government’s views during the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">18-months of intensive negotiations between the European Institutions</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a revised package of EU Procurement Directives. The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">agreed </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">package</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">support</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">our</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> priorities of economic growth and deficit reduction by making public procurement faster, less costly, and more effective for business and procurers alike. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We are supporting </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Cabinet Office </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> preparing ambitious plans for early transposition, so </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">we </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">can take advantage of the additional flexibilities in the new rules as soon as possible.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Questions</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">We have indicated above how DCLG, and central government as a whole, supports and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">incentivises</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> further progress in local government procurement. The following material sets our response to the questions asked by the Committee. As indicated, the Department does not intervene in the detail of local authority roles and responsibilities, but we have provided work undertaken in these areas, and examples of best practice for others to aim for.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Question 1</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">How procurement is structured in local government varies greatly. The Department is clear that different structures will suit different organisations. However, the ‘Best councils to do business with’ contest highlighted the need for procurement to be discussed at the top table. Each winner showed a clear procurement strategy, supported by council leadership, and linked in to wider strategies around economic development and growth.  For example, Manchester City Council has a Sustainable Procurement Strategy that shows how procurement supports wider objectives of the organisation and provides economic, social and environmental benefits. The London Borough of Harrow has a procurement policy that elevates procurement activity from ‘spend’ to ‘investment in the community’ </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">All strategies should identify the need to work with suppliers at all stages of the process, from pre-market engagement, to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">after</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> the contracts are awarded. They should identify how the council will manage the contract, particularly if it is long-term, to use them as a tool to build relationships with contractors, particularly in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">their local markets. Barnsley Metropolitan Borough Council awarded a £100 million 10 year contract through their Property Repairs and Improvement Partnership which utilised contract clauses to support social and economic regeneration. This resulted in £6 million being spent in the first year within the local supply chain, with 84% of directly employed personnel residing in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Barnsley</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">To support th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">ose strategies and th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">e wider objectives of procurement functions, DCLG published new Best Value guidance in September 2011</span><a name="_ftnref9"></a><a href="#_ftn9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">.  The guidance set out reasonable expectations of the way authorities should work with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">providers, including </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">allow</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> organisations and the community to put forward options on how to reshape the service.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">The Best Value Guidance is also clear that councils should consider overall value when reviewing service provision. This is complemented by the Public Services (Social Value) Act 2012 which requires public bodies to consider the economic, social, and environmental impact of their public service contracts at the pre procurement stage, and to consider consulting with service users. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Whilst </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the Department </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">do</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">es</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> not centrally monitor adherence to these objectives, the Mystery Shopper scheme investigate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> any complaints about the Act not being applied</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Question 2</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Significant savings can be achieved from collaboration opportunities in procurement. This can either be through a shared service arrangement, or through individual deals, including those supported by central government. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Consideration of shared services as a solution must now be automatic, particularly in a field like procurement where successful case studies are plentiful and benefits are relatively easy to gain. So we continue to press local authorities to go further on this agenda. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">One example of a shared service approach is Procurement Lincolnshire, which is a partnership between eight councils which has transformed services and improved outcomes for it’s customers. By working together, the partnership delivered £5.1 million in cashable savings in 2012/2013 through procurement. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">The Department agrees that local authorities </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">must</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> also take advantage of collaborative deals on specific categories of spend, particularly in high cost service areas. For example six councils around Oxfordshire have worked on jointly commissioning and procuring children’s homes and education services for children with complex needs. At least £2.5 million savings are estimated on the commissioning of 20-30 bed children’s homes and education services. This equates to about 15 per cent of annual cost of high cost residential placements for young people.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">During DCLG’s £250 million Weekly Collection Support Scheme a unique opportunity was created for the 82 successful councils to take advantage of joint procurement deals. Many were buying similar goods – wheeled bins and refuse collection vehicles – at a similar time within the thirty month timeframe allowed by the scheme.  Economies of scale would have meant cheaper products for those collaborating. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Despite a well-attended seminar and subsequent workshops, provided by DCLG with the LGA and other partners, it is felt that authorities did not take sufficient advantage of the procurement opportunity created from the Scheme. Excuses included: working to unique timescales; local sovereignty; and existing contracts, and these were complemented by a lack of understanding of processes and in some cases disinterest – a tunnel vision focused solely on the processes of their local authority. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Where local authorities have joined up, the advantages have been obvious. The London Waste and Recycling Board coordinated a joint procurement of food waste caddies and caddy liners. Around 250,000 caddies and 9.5 million liners were procured at a total cost of £460,000. This presented a saving over normal cost prices of 25 per cent. One authority did particularly well and achieved savings of 68 per cent compared to what it would have paid if it had procured alone. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">More examples of councils in receipt of Weekly Collection Support Scheme funding joining up to procure waste-related goods are emerging. The more examples presented to local authorities, the more likely it is that they will see the benefits and follow suit.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In support of this work, an </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">announcement </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">was </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">made on 24 July </span><a name="_ftnref10"></a><a href="#_ftn10">[10]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> that central government is creating a new commercial service for Government to act on behalf of the crown to drive savings for the taxpayer and to improve the quality of commercial and procurement acti</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">vity across the public sector. The Crown Commercial Service </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">will work closely with the wider public sector to ensure that the benefits of aggregation and centralisation are shared to maximise savings for the taxpayer</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Furthermore the forthcoming consultation on public sector procurement will also examine how transparent centrally negotiated deals are, and whether further data in this area will encourage greater take up. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Question 3</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Shared procurement services also provide an opportunity to create centres of expertise and capability, which maximise skills and market knowledge and create resilience, particularly for smaller councils. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Government Procurement Service also provide a range of training tools which are available to local government such as the free e-learning hub as well as access to professional procurement qualification packages. The</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">y</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> are at the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">beginning of a programme to roll out the training originally provided to NHS staff, to all central and local governme</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nt procurement/commercial staff</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. The Government Procurement Service have also accepted a few delegates from councils onto the courses aimed at central government officials and are managing levels of demand from local authorities against their current delivery capacity. They envisage an increase in numbers of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">local government</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> delegates over the next 6 to 12 months. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">They are also a source of skills, expertise, tools and resources that needs to be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">utilised</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> fully by councils.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="background-color:#ffff00; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">However the ‘Best Council’ winners showed how procurement skills must also be supported locally, either through professional qualifications, or by mechanisms for sharing best practice or concerns, such as Hertfordshire’s Contract Managers’ Network. More could be done to provide greater peer-support and ownership across local authorities. Whilst there are different opportunities to access to the right skills, there is still a culture of working in isolation that needs to be tackled. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Many councils have also identified spend analysis as a key tool. Support in this area is available from a range of sources, from the Government Procurement Service, to consultants, to in-house models. All the ‘Best Council’ winners identified mechanisms for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">analysing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> expenditure and examining markets. Surrey and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">East Sussex</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> share systems that provide profiles of a supply base and percentage of spend locally, in order to tailor procurement strategies. DCLG is working with the Local Government Association and the Government Procurement Service to examine how similar spend analysis tools could be made more available.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Question 4</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The ability to understand, assess and manage risk is critical to any procurement strategy that aims to reduce bureaucracy, encourage new innovative suppliers and achieve the best outcomes for the community.  The Federation of Small Businesses’ research indicates that councils are increasingly using different approaches to lower value, lower risk contract. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Many of the winners of the ‘Best Councils’ contest highlighted risk management as a key part of their procurement process. Halton Borough Council have adopted a process that is risk based not value driven, and which subsequently removes the requirement for Pre Qualification Questionnaires on lower value contracts. It makes the process simple and quick, with turn-around possible in 24 hours. They do not rule out suppliers purely on the basis of a credit reference report, they use all the information available to them. This approach has not only resulted in savings, but has also led to 89% of the council’s procurement spend going to small businesses. They also intend to review current supplier relationships over the next year.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Whilst this shows evidence of councils beginning to use risk to tailor tenders to the product and market place, there are still too many examples of over-burdensome selection criteria being applied to low risk contracts, discouraging small businesses from applying and wasting resources for all parties. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Councils also need to remove</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> unnecessary equality gold-plating, which can push up contract costs and make it </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">more difficult for small and voluntary organisations to bid for contracts</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">recommended by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Lord Young, and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">which will be examined further in the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> forthcoming publication of the public sector equal</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ity duty review. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Mystery Shopper Service provide</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> a clear, structured and direct route for suppliers to raise concerns about public procurement practice when attempts at resolving issues with a contracting authority or a first-tier supplier have failed. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Of the 155 local authority referrals, 32 related to Pre Qualification Questionnaires. That is why we need to do more to tackle this issue. Pre-qualification is a key theme in the forthcoming consultation on public sector procurement reform and we will act on the responses we receive to find a solution that eliminates unnecessary, disproportionate Pre Qualification Questionnaires. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Question 5 </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Councils operate within a robust set of financial regulations which aim to ensure regularity and propriety, as set out in the Department’s </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">accountability system statement. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Councils must have a Chief Finance Officer (or section 151 officer) in place who must advise immediately of any illegal spending. Councils must be audited every year by an independent auditor, who looks at the truth and fairness of the council’s financial statements, and their arrangements to achieve value for money. The auditor has the ability to produce a public interest report which examines concerns about at council’s approach to procurement. Recent examples of public interest reports on procurement include Wirral Borough Council’s highways contract, and regeneration schemes in Corby Borough Council.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">DCLG identified procurement fraud as one of the 50 Ways to Save, as it is estimated to cost local government around £880 million</span><a name="_ftnref11"></a><a href="#_ftn11">[11]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> a year. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Fighting </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Fraud Locally</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the local governm</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ent strategy for tackling fraud, was published in April 2012. D</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">eveloped by local government for local government, it addresses the need for greater prevention an</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">d smarter enforcement. I</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">t provides a blueprint for how </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">councils can reduce their</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> risk to fraud, realise cash savings, and work together to prevent future fraud losses</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. DCLG is a member of the Board charged with securing implementation of the strategy. Backed by guidance, case studies, advice on powers and penalties and discussion forums, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Fighting Fraud Locally</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> is an important conduit for councils to understand how they can prevent and tackle procurement fraud.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">he </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">National Fraud A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">uthority</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> is working with a small group of accountancy firms to develop some pilots with local authorities to provide good practice material on tackling procurement fraud</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. DCLG will soon be publishing a short guide setting out a few simple things that every organisation can do to prevent mandate fraud. The Government will also be publishing its response to its consultation on the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Code of Recommended Practice for Local Authorities on Data Transparency</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. This is likely to set out details about information which local authorities must be publishing on forthcoming procurement exercises and contracts that are awarded. Greater transparency should make an important contribution to combating fraud.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt; text-decoration:underline">Question 6</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Councils are accountable for the resources that they spend. Where they contract to other parties they are accountable for ensuring that appropriate arrangements are in place to ensure that the services is delivered, value for money is achieved, and where necessary, put contingency plans in place should the contractor fail to deliver the service.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">The Government</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">believes local </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">services should be accountable to local communities rather than</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Whitehall</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> It</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">continue</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> to reduce, unnecessary bureaucratic central performance management burdens on local </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">g</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">overnment, at the same time </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">it is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> strengthening local accountability measures such as transpa</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">rency.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">DCLG still has a role in assuring </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Parliament </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">public money it d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">istributes to local g</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">overnment is spent properly</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">The Department publishes its Accountability System Statement for local authorities. The statement sets out </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">the regulatory framework that is already in place for local bodies, to reassure Parliament and the public that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">councils</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> are spending their resources properly. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">The Mystery Shopper scheme also provides a mechanism for redress, as discussed above. Of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">143 closed cases involving </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">councils</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">, 87 resulted in a future or live procurement being adjusted</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Transparency is the foundation to local accountability and the key that gives people the tools and information they need to enable them to play a bigger role in society. The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Code of Recommended Practice for Local Authorities on Data Transparency</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> was issued, in September 2011, to meet the Government’s desire to place more power in citizen’s hands to increase democratic accountability and make it easier for local people to contribute to the local decision making process and help shape public services.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">The Code </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">list</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> key data which local authorities </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">are recommended to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">ublish, including</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> information around contracts and tenders to businesses and to the voluntary community and social enterprise sector.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> We recognise</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> that there is potential to go further. At the end of last year, we carried out a public consultation on updating the Code and making it mandatory in order to ensure greater accountability. We will publish the Government's response </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">shortly but it is likely to go further on procured goods and services than the current Code provides for.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">The forthcoming consultation of public sector procurement reforms will also examine the need for further transparency on procurement data. Between the Code and the consultation, councils and the general public will have a clear understanding of what data should be available on procurement. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 18pt 0pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/f